{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01UJVAjzk1RBGHfsyXBNuXQv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_0113B29UUTSqUrYH3aT86urM","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cd /tmp/codeharness-verify-8-9-semgrep-rules-rust-observability && claude --print --max-budget-usd 5 --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit -p \"You are a black-box verifier. Your job is to verify that a software feature works correctly from the user's perspective — using ONLY the installed CLI, documentation, and observability data. You have NO access to source code.\n\n## Why Black-Box Verification\n\nThis workspace contains NO source code. The src/ directory does not exist. This is intentional — you must verify the feature works as a user would experience it, not by reading implementation details.\n\n## Step 1: Read README.md\n\nStart by reading README.md in this workspace. It contains install and usage instructions.\n\n## Step 2: Review Acceptance Criteria\n\nThe story file story.md contains the acceptance criteria. Read it.\n\nThe ACs are:\n1. AC1: Given a Rust function without tracing macros or #[instrument], when Semgrep runs with rust-function-no-tracing rule, then it reports an observability gap\n2. AC2: Given a Rust match arm handling Err without tracing::error! or tracing::warn!, when Semgrep runs with rust-catch-without-tracing rule, then it reports an observability gap\n3. AC3: Given a Rust .map_err() or .unwrap_or_else() closure without tracing macros, when Semgrep runs with rust-error-path-no-tracing rule, then it reports an observability gap\n4. AC4: Given all 3 Rust rule files in patches/observability/, when codeharness audit runs on a Rust project with Semgrep installed, then the observability static analysis dimension uses the Rust rules automatically\n5. AC5: Given all changes, when npm test runs, then all existing tests pass with zero regressions\n\n## Step 3: Verify Each AC\n\nFor EACH acceptance criterion, you must:\n1. Run commands inside the Docker container via docker exec codeharness-verify ...\n2. Capture the command output as evidence\n3. Query observability endpoints if runtime evidence is needed\n\n### Docker Container\n- Container name: codeharness-verify\n- ALL CLI commands MUST run via: docker exec codeharness-verify <command>\n\nThe container has: codeharness, semgrep, node, npm, curl, jq installed.\n\n### Verification Strategy for Semgrep Rules\n\nFor AC1, AC2, AC3:\n1. First, validate each rule with: docker exec codeharness-verify semgrep --validate --config /opt/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-<rule>.yaml\n2. Create sample Rust files INSIDE the container that should trigger findings\n3. Create sample Rust files that should NOT trigger findings (have proper tracing)\n4. Run semgrep scan against the samples and verify correct detection\n\nFor AC2 specifically — this was previously broken because Err(\\$E) => { ... } is not a standalone Rust expression. The fix wraps patterns in match \\$X { ... }. Verify semgrep --validate passes AND that the rule actually detects untraced Err arms.\n\nFor AC4: Run codeharness audit on a sample Rust project in the container and verify Rust rules are picked up.\n\nFor AC5: Tests cannot run in the container (not shipped in npm package). Verify the CLI is functional: docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness --version\n\n### Observability Endpoints\nQuery these from the HOST for runtime evidence:\n- VictoriaLogs: http://localhost:9428\n- VictoriaMetrics: http://localhost:8428\n- VictoriaTraces: http://localhost:16686\n\nAfter EACH docker exec command, query: curl 'http://localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=_stream_id:*&start=-30s&limit=100'\n\n## Step 4: Write Proof Document\n\nWrite your verification proof to: verification/8-9-semgrep-rules-rust-observability-proof.md\n\nUse this format for each AC:\n## AC N: <description>\n\n\\`\\`\\`bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify <command>\n\\`\\`\\`\n\n\\`\\`\\`output\n<actual output>\n\\`\\`\\`\n\nIMPORTANT: Only use bash and output as code fence languages. Never use bare fences without a language tag.\n\n## Critical Rules\n\n1. ALL commands MUST use docker exec codeharness-verify ...\n2. Do NOT attempt to access source code\n3. Report REAL failures — never fabricate evidence\n4. Every AC needs functional evidence\n5. [ESCALATE] is ONLY for things genuinely impossible to automate — NOT for infrastructure problems\n6. Never switch to unit-testable verification\" 2>&1","description":"Run black-box verifier session","timeout":300000},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5751,"cache_read_input_tokens":53677,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5751},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6dce843f-9ba8-4a40-8e6f-55f9620fecc1","uuid":"236bb51a-f694-4332-b4b8-0cfd415f650f"}
