{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AnxhzYoHh1kPRNpMX22s3H","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Story 8.9: Semgrep Rules — Rust Observability — Verification Proof\n     2→\n     3→**Date:** 2026-03-23\n     4→**Verifier:** Claude Opus 4.6 (black-box)\n     5→**Container:** codeharness-verify\n     6→**codeharness version:** 0.23.1\n     7→**Semgrep version:** 1.156.0\n     8→\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→## AC1: rust-function-no-tracing rule detects Rust functions without tracing macros\n    12→\n    13→**Result: PASS**\n    14→\n    15→### Step 1: Validate rule\n    16→\n    17→```bash\n    18→docker exec codeharness-verify semgrep --validate --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.yaml\n    19→```\n    20→\n    21→```output\n    22→Configuration is valid - found 0 configuration error(s), and 1 rule(s).\n    23→```\n    24→\n    25→### Step 2: Scan test file with positive and negative cases\n    26→\n    27→Test file contains 3 functions WITHOUT tracing (should trigger) and 3 functions WITH tracing (should not trigger).\n    28→\n    29→```bash\n    30→docker exec codeharness-verify semgrep --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.yaml /tmp/rust-test/test_ac1.rs\n    31→```\n    32→\n    33→```output\n    34→┌─────────────────┐\n    35→│ 3 Code Findings │\n    36→└─────────────────┘\n    37→\n    38→    /tmp/rust-test/test_ac1.rs\n    39→     ❱ rust-function-no-tracing\n    40→          Rust function without tracing instrumentation — observability gap\n    41→\n    42→            2┆ fn process_data(x: i32) -> i32 {\n    43→            3┆     x + 1\n    44→            4┆ }\n    45→            ⋮┆----------------------------------------\n    46→            6┆ pub fn handle_request(req: String) -> String {\n    47→            7┆     req.to_uppercase()\n    48→            8┆ }\n    49→            ⋮┆----------------------------------------\n    50→           10┆ async fn fetch_data() -> Result<String, String> {\n    51→           11┆     Ok(\"data\".to_string())\n    52→           12┆ }\n    53→\n    54→Ran 1 rule on 1 file: 3 findings.\n    55→```\n    56→\n    57→**Analysis:** 3 findings on untraced functions (`process_data`, `handle_request`, `fetch_data`). Zero findings on functions with `#[tracing::instrument]`, `tracing::info!()`, or `debug!()`. Correct behavior.\n    58→\n    59→---\n    60→\n    61→## AC2: rust-catch-without-tracing rule detects Rust Err match arms without tracing::error!/warn!\n    62→\n    63→**Result: FAIL**\n    64→\n    65→### Step 1: Validate rule\n    66→\n    67→```bash\n    68→docker exec codeharness-verify semgrep --validate --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-catch-without-tracing.yaml\n    69→```\n    70→\n    71→```output\n    72→Configuration is invalid - found 1 configuration error(s), and 1 rule(s).\n    73→[ERROR] Pattern parse error in rule rust-catch-without-tracing:\n    74→ Invalid pattern for Rust:\n    75→--- pattern ---\n    76→match $X {\n    77→  ...\n    78→  Err($E) => { ... }\n    79→  ...\n    80→}\n    81→\n    82→--- end pattern ---\n    83→Pattern error: Stdlib.Parsing.Parse_error\n    84→```\n    85→\n    86→**Analysis:** The rule wraps `Err($E) => { ... }` inside `match $X { ... }` (the documented fix for the previous broken version). However, Semgrep's Rust parser (v1.156.0) cannot parse this pattern — it fails with `Stdlib.Parsing.Parse_error`. The `match` expression with ellipsis arms is not supported as a Semgrep pattern for Rust.\n    87→\n    88→This means the fix described in the story (\"wraps patterns in `match $X { ... }`\") does not resolve the underlying issue — Semgrep's Rust parser simply does not support this pattern construct.\n    89→\n    90→---\n    91→\n    92→## AC3: rust-error-path-no-tracing rule detects .map_err()/.unwrap_or_else() closures without tracing\n    93→\n    94→**Result: PASS**\n    95→\n    96→### Step 1: Validate rule\n    97→\n    98→```bash\n    99→docker exec codeharness-verify semgrep --validate --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-error-path-no-tracing.yaml\n   100→```\n   101→\n   102→```output\n   103→Configuration is valid - found 0 configuration error(s), and 1 rule(s).\n   104→```\n   105→\n   106→### Step 2: Scan test file with positive and negative cases\n   107→\n   108→Test file contains 2 closures WITHOUT tracing (should trigger) and 2 closures WITH tracing (should not trigger).\n   109→\n   110→```bash\n   111→docker exec codeharness-verify semgrep --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-error-path-no-tracing.yaml /tmp/rust-test/test_ac3.rs\n   112→```\n   113→\n   114→```output\n   115→┌─────────────────┐\n   116→│ 2 Code Findings │\n   117→└─────────────────┘\n   118→\n   119→    /tmp/rust-test/test_ac3.rs\n   120→     ❱ rust-error-path-no-tracing\n   121→          Rust error-path closure without tracing — observability gap\n   122→\n   123→            3┆ let result = some_call().map_err(|e| {\n   124→            4┆     println!(\"error: {}\", e);\n   125→            5┆     e\n   126→            6┆ });\n   127→            ⋮┆----------------------------------------\n   128→            8┆ let val = other_call().unwrap_or_else(|e| {\n   129→            9┆     eprintln!(\"failed: {}\", e);\n   130→           10┆     Default::default()\n   131→           11┆ });\n   132→\n   133→Ran 1 rule on 1 file: 2 findings.\n   134→```\n   135→\n   136→**Analysis:** 2 findings on untraced closures (`map_err` and `unwrap_or_else` without tracing). Zero findings on closures with `tracing::error!()` or `warn!()`. Correct behavior.\n   137→\n   138→---\n   139→\n   140→## AC4: All 3 rules auto-discovered by codeharness audit on a Rust project\n   141→\n   142→**Result: PARTIAL FAIL**\n   143→\n   144→### Step 1: Create minimal Rust project and initialize codeharness\n   145→\n   146→```bash\n   147→docker exec codeharness-verify bash -c 'cd /tmp/rust-project && codeharness init --no-observability'\n   148→```\n   149→\n   150→```output\n   151→[INFO] Stack detected: Rust (Cargo.toml)\n   152→[OK] Semgrep: already installed (v1.156.0)\n   153→[OK] Enforcement: frontend:ON database:ON api:ON observability:ON\n   154→```\n   155→\n   156→### Step 2: Copy rules to project patches dir and run audit\n   157→\n   158→Rules must be manually copied to `patches/observability/` — they are not auto-discovered from the global npm install path.\n   159→\n   160→```bash\n   161→docker exec codeharness-verify bash -c 'cd /tmp/rust-project && codeharness audit'\n   162→```\n   163→\n   164→```output\n   165→[WARN] observability: static: skipped (analysis failed), runtime: skipped (validation failed)\n   166→  [WARN] Static analysis failed: Semgrep scan failed: Error: Command failed: semgrep scan --config /tmp/rust-project/patches/observability/ --json /tmp/rust-project\n   167→\n   168→  Scanning 1 file with 3 rust rules.\n   169→\n   170→  ✅ Scan completed successfully.\n   171→   • Findings: 2 (2 blocking)\n   172→   • Rules run: 3\n   173→   • Targets scanned: 1\n   174→\n   175→  Ran 3 rules on 1 file: 2 findings.\n   176→   -- fix: Check Semgrep installation and rules configuration\n   177→\n   178→[WARN] Audit complete: 5 gaps found (1219ms)\n   179→```\n   180→\n   181→**Analysis:** All 3 Rust rules ARE loaded (\"3 rust rules\") and the scan runs successfully finding 2 issues. However, the audit reports \"analysis failed\" because the AC2 rule's parse error causes Semgrep to return a non-zero exit code, which codeharness interprets as a scan failure.\n   182→\n   183→Two issues with auto-discovery:\n   184→1. Rules are not auto-linked from the global npm path — manual copy to `patches/observability/` is required\n   185→2. The AC2 parse error poisons the entire scan result, causing audit to report failure despite AC1 and AC3 working correctly\n   186→\n   187→---\n   188→\n   189→## AC5: All tests pass with zero regressions (CLI functional check only)\n   190→\n   191→**Result: PASS**\n   192→\n   193→```bash\n   194→docker exec codeharness-verify codeharness --version\n   195→```\n   196→\n   197→```output\n   198→0.23.1\n   199→```\n   200→\n   201→CLI is functional. Rules AC1 and AC3 validate and scan correctly. AC2 is the only regression — it fails Semgrep validation.\n   202→\n   203→---\n   204→\n   205→## Observability Check\n   206→\n   207→```bash\n   208→curl 'http://localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=*&start=-60s&limit=10'\n   209→```\n   210→\n   211→```output\n   212→(no logs — OTLP not configured in container)\n   213→```\n   214→\n   215→---\n   216→\n   217→## Summary\n   218→\n   219→| AC | Description | Result |\n   220→|----|-------------|--------|\n   221→| AC1 | rust-function-no-tracing detection | **PASS** |\n   222→| AC2 | rust-catch-without-tracing detection | **FAIL** — Semgrep Rust parser cannot parse `match $X { ... Err($E) => { ... } ... }` pattern |\n   223→| AC3 | rust-error-path-no-tracing detection | **PASS** |\n   224→| AC4 | Auto-discovery by codeharness audit | **PARTIAL FAIL** — rules load but audit reports failure due to AC2 parse error; rules not auto-linked from global path |\n   225→| AC5 | CLI functional check | **PASS** |\n   226→\n   227→**Overall: FAIL** — AC2 rule is broken. The `match` pattern with ellipsis arms is not valid Semgrep Rust syntax. This blocks AC4 as well since the parse error causes the entire audit scan to report failure.\n   228→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6dce843f-9ba8-4a40-8e6f-55f9620fecc1","uuid":"04ce1adc-ef95-48e5-a1ee-2ab112da17b7","timestamp":"2026-03-23T09:14:21.102Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/codeharness-verify-8-9-semgrep-rules-rust-observability/verification/8-9-semgrep-rules-rust-observability-proof.md","content":"# Story 8.9: Semgrep Rules — Rust Observability — Verification Proof\n\n**Date:** 2026-03-23\n**Verifier:** Claude Opus 4.6 (black-box)\n**Container:** codeharness-verify\n**codeharness version:** 0.23.1\n**Semgrep version:** 1.156.0\n\n---\n\n## AC1: rust-function-no-tracing rule detects Rust functions without tracing macros\n\n**Result: PASS**\n\n### Step 1: Validate rule\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify semgrep --validate --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.yaml\n```\n\n```output\nConfiguration is valid - found 0 configuration error(s), and 1 rule(s).\n```\n\n### Step 2: Scan test file with positive and negative cases\n\nTest file contains 3 functions WITHOUT tracing (should trigger) and 3 functions WITH tracing (should not trigger).\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify semgrep --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-function-no-tracing.yaml /tmp/rust-test/test_ac1.rs\n```\n\n```output\n┌─────────────────┐\n│ 3 Code Findings │\n└─────────────────┘\n\n    /tmp/rust-test/test_ac1.rs\n     ❱ rust-function-no-tracing\n          Rust function without tracing instrumentation — observability gap\n\n            2┆ fn process_data(x: i32) -> i32 {\n            3┆     x + 1\n            4┆ }\n            ⋮┆----------------------------------------\n            6┆ pub fn handle_request(req: String) -> String {\n            7┆     req.to_uppercase()\n            8┆ }\n            ⋮┆----------------------------------------\n           10┆ async fn fetch_data() -> Result<String, String> {\n           11┆     Ok(\"data\".to_string())\n           12┆ }\n\nRan 1 rule on 1 file: 3 findings.\n```\n\n**Analysis:** 3 findings on untraced functions (`process_data`, `handle_request`, `fetch_data`). Zero findings on functions with `#[tracing::instrument]`, `tracing::info!()`, or `debug!()`. Correct behavior.\n\n---\n\n## AC2: rust-catch-without-tracing rule detects Rust Err match arms without tracing::error!/warn!\n\n**Result: FAIL**\n\n### Step 1: Validate rule\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify semgrep --validate --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-catch-without-tracing.yaml\n```\n\n```output\nConfiguration is invalid - found 1 configuration error(s), and 1 rule(s).\n[ERROR] Pattern parse error in rule rust-catch-without-tracing:\n Invalid pattern for Rust:\n--- pattern ---\nmatch $X {\n  ...\n  Err($E) => { ... }\n  ...\n}\n\n--- end pattern ---\nPattern error: Stdlib.Parsing.Parse_error\n```\n\n**Analysis:** The rule wraps `Err($E) => { ... }` inside `match $X { ... }` (the documented fix for the previous broken version). However, Semgrep's Rust parser (v1.156.0) cannot parse this pattern — it fails with `Stdlib.Parsing.Parse_error`. The `match` expression with ellipsis arms is not supported as a Semgrep pattern for Rust.\n\nThis means the fix described in the story (\"wraps patterns in `match $X { ... }`\") does not resolve the underlying issue — Semgrep's Rust parser simply does not support this pattern construct.\n\n---\n\n## AC3: rust-error-path-no-tracing rule detects .map_err()/.unwrap_or_else() closures without tracing\n\n**Result: PASS**\n\n### Step 1: Validate rule\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify semgrep --validate --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-error-path-no-tracing.yaml\n```\n\n```output\nConfiguration is valid - found 0 configuration error(s), and 1 rule(s).\n```\n\n### Step 2: Scan test file with positive and negative cases\n\nTest file contains 2 closures WITHOUT tracing (should trigger) and 2 closures WITH tracing (should not trigger).\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify semgrep --config /usr/local/lib/node_modules/codeharness/patches/observability/rust-error-path-no-tracing.yaml /tmp/rust-test/test_ac3.rs\n```\n\n```output\n┌─────────────────┐\n│ 2 Code Findings │\n└─────────────────┘\n\n    /tmp/rust-test/test_ac3.rs\n     ❱ rust-error-path-no-tracing\n          Rust error-path closure without tracing — observability gap\n\n            3┆ let result = some_call().map_err(|e| {\n            4┆     println!(\"error: {}\", e);\n            5┆     e\n            6┆ });\n            ⋮┆----------------------------------------\n            8┆ let val = other_call().unwrap_or_else(|e| {\n            9┆     eprintln!(\"failed: {}\", e);\n           10┆     Default::default()\n           11┆ });\n\nRan 1 rule on 1 file: 2 findings.\n```\n\n**Analysis:** 2 findings on untraced closures (`map_err` and `unwrap_or_else` without tracing). Zero findings on closures with `tracing::error!()` or `warn!()`. Correct behavior.\n\n---\n\n## AC4: All 3 rules auto-discovered by codeharness audit on a Rust project\n\n**Result: PARTIAL FAIL**\n\n### Step 1: Create minimal Rust project and initialize codeharness\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify bash -c 'cd /tmp/rust-project && codeharness init --no-observability'\n```\n\n```output\n[INFO] Stack detected: Rust (Cargo.toml)\n[OK] Semgrep: already installed (v1.156.0)\n[OK] Enforcement: frontend:ON database:ON api:ON observability:ON\n```\n\n### Step 2: Copy rules to project patches dir and run audit\n\nRules must be manually copied to `patches/observability/` — they are not auto-discovered from the global npm install path.\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify bash -c 'cd /tmp/rust-project && codeharness audit'\n```\n\n```output\n[WARN] observability: static: skipped (analysis failed), runtime: skipped (validation failed)\n  [WARN] Static analysis failed: Semgrep scan failed: Error: Command failed: semgrep scan --config /tmp/rust-project/patches/observability/ --json /tmp/rust-project\n\n  Scanning 1 file with 3 rust rules.\n\n  ✅ Scan completed successfully.\n   • Findings: 2 (2 blocking)\n   • Rules run: 3\n   • Targets scanned: 1\n\n  Ran 3 rules on 1 file: 2 findings.\n   -- fix: Check Semgrep installation and rules configuration\n\n[WARN] Audit complete: 5 gaps found (1219ms)\n```\n\n**Analysis:** All 3 Rust rules ARE loaded (\"3 rust rules\") and the scan runs successfully finding 2 issues. However, the audit reports \"analysis failed\" because the AC2 rule's parse error causes Semgrep to return a non-zero exit code, which codeharness interprets as a scan failure.\n\nTwo issues with auto-discovery:\n1. Rules are not auto-linked from the global npm path — manual copy to `patches/observability/` is required\n2. The AC2 parse error poisons the entire scan result, causing audit to report failure despite AC1 and AC3 working correctly\n\n---\n\n## AC5: All tests pass with zero regressions (CLI functional check only)\n\n**Result: PASS**\n\n```bash\ndocker exec codeharness-verify codeharness --version\n```\n\n```output\n0.23.1\n```\n\nCLI is functional. Rules AC1 and AC3 validate and scan correctly. AC2 is the only regression — it fails Semgrep validation.\n\n---\n\n## Observability Check\n\n```bash\ncurl 'http://localhost:9428/select/logsql/query?query=*&start=-60s&limit=10'\n```\n\n```output\n(no logs — OTLP not configured in container)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n| AC | Description | Result |\n|----|-------------|--------|\n| AC1 | rust-function-no-tracing detection | **PASS** |\n| AC2 | rust-catch-without-tracing detection | **FAIL** — Semgrep Rust parser cannot parse `match $X { ... Err($E) => { ... } ... }` pattern |\n| AC3 | rust-error-path-no-tracing detection | **PASS** |\n| AC4 | Auto-discovery by codeharness audit | **PARTIAL FAIL** — rules load but audit reports failure due to AC2 parse error; rules not auto-linked from global path |\n| AC5 | CLI functional check | **PASS** |\n\n**Overall: FAIL** — AC2 rule is broken. The `match` pattern with ellipsis arms is not valid Semgrep Rust syntax. This blocks AC4 as well since the parse error causes the entire audit scan to report failure.\n","numLines":228,"startLine":1,"totalLines":228}}}
